# Nmap Quick Reference & NSE Basics

A compact, practical guide to Nmap — installation, common scan types, examples, NSE (Nmap Scripting Engine) usage, and a tiny example NSE script.

---

## What is Nmap?
Nmap (Network Mapper) is an open-source tool for network discovery and security auditing.  
It finds hosts, open ports, services, versions, OS fingerprints, and can run scripts to check for common issues.

---

## Install
Download the installer from [nmap.org] or use your package manager.  
Verify installation: nmap --version

##Basic concepts / results

Open — service accepting connections on that port.
Closed — reachable but no service listening.
Filtered — packet filtering (firewall) is blocking probes.
Host up/down — whether host responded to probes (ICMP/TCP/etc).

##Common scan types (quick cheat)

-sS — TCP SYN (stealth) scan (fast, needs raw sockets/root).
-sT — TCP connect() (no raw sockets; slower; used if not root).
-sU — UDP scan (slower, useful for DNS, SNMP).
-sV — Service/version detection.
-O — OS detection.
-A — Aggressive; includes -sV -O + scripts + traceroute.
-p <ports> — Port selection: 80, 1-1000, - for all -p-.
-Pn — Skip host discovery (treat host as up).
-T0..T5 — Timing template (0 slowest / 5 fastest). -T4 common for LAN.
--open — show only open ports.
-oN/-oX/-oG/-oA — Save output: normal, XML, grepable, all formats.

##Useful examples

Scan single host, top 1000 ports: nmap 192.168.1.10
Stealth + version detect + show only open: sudo nmap -sS -sV --open 192.168.1.10 -T4
Scan full TCP port range: sudo nmap -p- 192.168.1.10
Quick UDP scan for some common ports: sudo nmap -sU -p 53,67,68,69,123 192.168.1.10 -T3
Aggressive scan (more noisy): sudo nmap -A 192.168.1.0/24 -T4
Skip ping (useful when ICMP blocked): sudo nmap -Pn 10.0.0.5 -p 22,80 -sV
Save outputs in multiple formats: sudo nmap -sS -sV 192.168.1.0/24 -oA lan_scan              
                                  This produces lan_scan.nmap, lan_scan.xml, lan_scan.gnmap.

##Using NSE (Nmap Scripting Engine)
NSE scripts can detect vulnerabilities, misconfigurations, brute-force, etc.

List installed scripts (path may vary by OS; common Linux path shown):
List scripts: ls /usr/share/nmap/scripts/ (path varies)

Run specific script: sudo nmap --script=http-title -p80 192.168.1.10
Run categories (vuln, auth, discovery): sudo nmap --script=vuln 192.168.1.10
